<br>
First, you must make clear what your guild goals are.  You cannot possibly have fun unless you have some sort of direction (to find like minded folks).<br>
<br>
Types of Guilds:<br>
Newb guild - friends and adventure<br>
Friends guild - Chat, fun, but nothing matters except friends.<br>
Raider wanna-bes - Try hard but fail and cause frustration in the ranks.<br>
Raiding guild - Heavy hitters.<br>
<br>
You have to decide what *fun* is for you and your guildies.  After you decide, you need to make a charter to express the direction of the guild and stick with it.<br>
<br>
I have been an officer of a several guilds.  I have created two guilds from nothing.  My first guild was a raiding guild.  They are doing fairly well to this day, I'm proud to say.  However, that wasn't for me.  I'm too old to make my game that much work and I was missing the things that made it fun.  So I created my second guild.  A friends guild.  Sure most of us are very skilled and lvl 55+, but really all we care about is spending time together and having fun.  If we take down some_named_mob_001 we usually end up saying something along the lines of &quot;Oh yeah, mobs down.&quot; /shrug.<br>
<br>
Its relative.  Make sure you know what makes it fun for you and stick with it.  It took me several years of EQ to get back to what is fun for me. <p><p><br>
